A study in Portugal revealed that a significant number of sexually active girls aged 15-19 use emergency contraception, with some not using any birth control at all.
Despite receiving contraceptive information in school, risks remain high for young women.
In Peru, controversy surrounds the distribution of morning-after pills, with accusations of promoting abortion.
The debate extends to the US, where access to emergency contraception is restricted in some states.
The issue highlights the ongoing clash between conservative beliefs and public health concerns, emphasizing the need for comprehensive reproductive health policies.
